(window.WISE_WORLD_Q = window.WISE_WORLD_Q || {}).en = [
  { id:1, topic:"Hand washing science", emoji:"🧼",
    question:"When your hands have germs or viruses on them, why does washing with 'soap' make them far safer than washing with water alone?",
    choices:["The shape of the soap bubbles startles the germs and chases them far away","Soap can completely break apart the oily film (the outer membrane) that wraps around a virus, dissolving it","Soap makes the skin on your hands as hard as iron so it repels germs","The smell of soap stops the germs from breathing"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The surface of many germs and viruses (like the flu) is actually protected by a thin film of fat called 'lipid.' This film is what gives them the power to invade the human body. Fat can never be washed off with water alone, but soap molecules have the power to surround fat and dissolve it in water. When you scrub your hands with soap, the oily film protecting the virus is dissolved to pieces in an instant, the virus can no longer stay alive, and it is completely destroyed. Washing with soap doesn't just rinse germs off your hands - it is the strongest medicine for scientifically wiping out the enemy." },
  { id:2, topic:"Direct pressure", emoji:"🩹",
    question:"When you have a deep wound and blood is pouring out, what is the very first 'correct first aid (direct pressure)' you should do to save a life?",
    choices:["Keep gently stroking the wound with a cloth dampened with water","Place a clean cloth directly on the wound and press down hard from above, putting your body weight into it","Swing the wound around wildly until the bleeding stops","Pack mud around the wound to stop the blood"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Losing a large amount of blood is the greatest danger of all - oxygen stops reaching your cells and you can lose your life in moments. The world-wide basic of medicine that prevents this is 'direct pressure.' By pressing the torn blood vessel hard from the outside, you physically close off the path the blood travels. On top of that, pressing helps the 'platelets' in your blood - the team that builds the scab - gather at the wound and patch up the torn hole. Gently wiping halfheartedly will not stop the bleeding. The wisdom of pressing hard with both hands keeps someone alive." },
  { id:3, topic:"Splinting a fracture", emoji:"🦴",
    question:"When you suspect 'a broken bone in the leg or arm (a fracture)' after a fall, why must you absolutely never force that spot to move?",
    choices:["Moving it makes the bone suddenly turn into a round ball","The sharp end of the broken bone can shred the important muscles, blood vessels, and nerves inside the skin, causing heavy bleeding or paralysis","Moving the bone makes the bone ten times heavier","The bone gets surprised and disappears from inside the body"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"When a bone snaps inside the skin, the broken end is extremely sharp and pointed, like a shard of glass. If you force the spot to move - wondering 'can I still walk?' - that pointed bone blade moves around inside your clothes and muscles, slicing a thick nearby blood vessel and causing internal bleeding, or damaging a nerve and causing paralysis that never heals. When a fracture is suspected, place a tree branch or a hard board (a splint) and fix the joint above and the joint below the break at the same time, so it cannot move even a millimeter while you wait for treatment. That is the correct emergency wisdom." },
  { id:4, topic:"Treating a burn", emoji:"🔥",
    question:"When you touch fire or hot water and get a burn, what is the very first thing you must do, in a great hurry, before anything else?",
    choices:["Spread oil or mud on the wound to keep it from drying out","Cool the wound with clean cold water, keeping it there for at least 15 minutes, until the pain eases","Peel off the burned skin neatly with your fingernails","Wrap it in a warm cloth to keep it warm"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The frightening thing about a burn is that even after you pull away from the hot object, the tremendous heat energy left on the surface of the skin keeps soaking deeper inside (into the dermis and muscle layers) like a burning coal, destroying cells. The only way to stop this is to steal the heat away as fast as possible with cold water. Cooling for over 15 minutes stops the wave of heat moving inward and keeps the injury as shallow as possible. If the early cooling is not enough, the skin dies deeply, leaving a large scar for life and making it easy for germs to invade. Cooling with water is science's brake on the spread of a burn." },
  { id:5, topic:"Oral rehydration", emoji:"🥤",
    question:"When severe diarrhea or vomiting leaves your body bone-dry, why is it scientifically better to drink water mixed with a little 'salt' and 'sugar' (oral rehydration solution) than to drink plain water?",
    choices:["Mixing salt and sugar makes the water taste good so you feel better","The wall of the small intestine has a special door that absorbs water at tremendous speed when the salt part (sodium) and the sugar part (glucose) arrive together","The salt directly burns and kills the diarrhea germs","Drinking sugar instantly freezes your stomach and stops the diarrhea"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"During severe diarrhea or vomiting, the wall of your gut is damaged, so even plain water cannot be absorbed well and just passes out the other end. But the wall of the human small intestine has a door (SGLT-1) that, when sodium and glucose arrive together in a balance of 1 to 2, sucks water into the cells in an instant like a powerful pump. The thing that uses this is 'oral rehydration solution,' which has saved many lives around the world. This magic water - made by mixing half a teaspoon of salt and four and a half tablespoons of sugar into one liter of water - can reliably save a life from dehydration even where there is no IV drip. It is the wisdom of medicine." },
  { id:6, topic:"Immune memory", emoji:"💉",
    question:"Once a person catches a certain strong illness, such as measles, they rarely catch the same illness again. What do we call this wonderful system inside the body?",
    choices:["Bone rejuvenation","The memory system of immunity","Crystallization of the blood","An illusion of the brain"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Inside our bodies, an immune team - including 'white blood cells' that fight germs and viruses - patrols 24 hours a day. When a vicious virus invades for the first time, it takes many days to build the weapon (an antibody) to fight it, and during that time you can become seriously ill. But the amazing thing about the immune team is that it completely memorizes the shape and features of an enemy it has fought once, storing it in the brain and cells. Years later, when the same enemy invades again, it uses that memory to create huge amounts of the exact weapon in an instant and wipes the enemy out with a single blow before you even get sick. The technology that applies this - safely planting just the memory before you get sick - is the 'vaccine (immunization).'" },
  { id:7, topic:"If an animal bites you", emoji:"🐕",
    question:"When a wild dog, fox, bat, or other animal bites you, even if the wound looks small, why must you rush to wash it out with lots of water and soap - a matter of life and death?",
    choices:["The color on the animal's teeth might transfer onto your skin","The animal's saliva may hide a terrifying virus like rabies, which destroys the brain and kills nearly 100% of the people it infects","If you don't wash, new fur will grow from the bitten spot","To show the animal your thanks"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Around the world there is a terrifying disease called 'rabies,' which spreads to humans when an animal carrying the virus bites them. If this virus enters the body and travels along the nerves all the way to the brain, then once symptoms appear, even modern medicine almost never saves the person and they die. However, there is a short window of time before the virus enters the nerves from the wound. Right after the bite, washing the wound fiercely under lots of running clean water and soap for over 15 minutes physically rinses away and reduces the virus stuck to the wound, and can stop it from reaching the brain. If an animal bites you, 'wash hard above all else first' - this is the absolute rule of medicine that decides life and death." },
  { id:8, topic:"Venomous creatures", emoji:"🐍",
    question:"When a venomous snake, spider, or other dangerous creature bites your hand or foot, which is the 'wrong action' you must absolutely never do?",
    choices:["Keep the bitten spot from moving and lie down quietly","Panic, shout loudly, and run around frantically to escape","Tell a nearby adult exactly what kind of creature bit you","Keep the wound lower than your heart"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"When a venomous creature bites you, if you panic with fear and run around or make a big fuss, your heartbeat (your pulse) speeds up sharply. Then the venom that entered the wound rides the fast-flowing blood and spreads in an instant to the muscles, brain, and organs of your whole body, so the venom spreads dramatically faster and you can lose your life. If something venomous bites you, the correct response is to calm your heart, not run, not move, and lie down quietly and still. By keeping the wound a little lower than your heart, you can slow the speed at which the venom-carrying blood returns to your heart. Staying calm and still is the very shield that stops the venom from spreading." },
  { id:9, topic:"Sweat and salt", emoji:"💦",
    question:"On a hot day, after you sweat a great deal, why does drinking only large amounts of 'plain water with no salt' all at once actually make you feel worse?",
    choices:["Drinking plain water makes the water in your stomach rot","Because salt (sodium) is lost from the body along with the sweat, drinking only water makes the salt level in your blood too thin, so the brain and muscles can't work properly (low sodium)","Too much water makes all the bones in your body dissolve","Plain water turns your blood from red to blue"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Your body fluids (such as blood) always contain about 0.9% salt, and thanks to this exquisite level, the commands of your nerves pass correctly to your muscles and brain. When you sweat a lot, this important salt leaks out along with the water. If you then pour only plain water with no salt into that empty body, the salt level inside gets even thinner. The brain then judges 'if this gets any thinner it's dangerous!' and refuses the water, or tries to throw the water out as sweat or urine. As a result, your legs cramp hard (heat cramps), and you get headaches and dizziness. When replenishing fluids on a hot day, you must always take in just a little salt at the same time." },
  { id:10, topic:"Opening the airway", emoji:"😮",
    question:"When someone collapses, unconscious, and may not be breathing, what is the real purpose of putting them in the position of lifting the chin up and tilting the head back (opening the airway)?",
    choices:["Turning the face up so sunlight can enter the eyes","When you lose consciousness, the big muscle deep in the throat (the root of the tongue) flops down and completely blocks the path of air, so this prevents suffocation","To straighten the neck bones and make the person taller","To help the collapsed person sleep more easily"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"When a person loses consciousness and goes completely limp, the muscle of the tongue deep in the throat also sinks loosely back into the throat. This is called 'the tongue falling back.' The throat of a person lying face-up gets completely capped off - the path of air (the airway) is blocked by their own tongue - so they cannot breathe and suffocate. To prevent this, while pressing on the forehead, use your other hand to firmly lift the chin bone up toward the sky. This physically pulls the space deep in the throat open wide, so air can reach the lungs smoothly. This 'opening the airway' is the world-wide first step of life-saving, done before rescue breaths or chest compressions." },
  { id:11, topic:"How breathing works", emoji:"💨",
    question:"When we breathe in and out, why must our body throw out the gas called 'carbon dioxide'?",
    choices:["If carbon dioxide builds up in the body, your skin turns green","Carbon dioxide is poisonous waste produced when cells burn nutrients to move energetically, and if it builds up in the blood, the blood turns acidic and becomes life-threatening","If you don't breathe out carbon dioxide, your body swells up like a balloon and floats into the sky","To keep the inside of your body cold"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Just as a car burns gasoline and gives off exhaust, the trillions of cells in a human burn the nutrients of food using oxygen to make the energy to live, and they always create the exhaust waste called 'carbon dioxide.' When a lot of this dissolves into the blood, it has the poisonous power to rapidly change the blood from neutral to a dangerous acid. When the blood turns acidic, the cells of the brain and heart can no longer work, and the person dies. That is exactly why the heart rushes the blood to the lungs, throwing out carbon dioxide one second faster through breathing and taking in fresh oxygen in its place, again and again." },
  { id:12, topic:"What the heart does", emoji:"❤️",
    question:"What is the real purpose of the 'heart' on the left side of your chest beating without rest, not even for one second, from the moment we are born until we die?",
    choices:["To grind up and break down the food inside your stomach","To circulate a 'body courier' that carries blood full of oxygen and nutrients to the cells of the whole body and collects the waste (such as carbon dioxide) the cells give off","To push out the extra water that has built up inside the body","To make the heart's sound echo so it tells your friends where you are"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The heart is a very powerful muscle pump that moves the blood flowing through our bodies. The blood carries the oxygen received in the lungs and the nutrients absorbed in the gut, delivering them to cells from the top of the head to the tips of the toes - it plays the role of an important courier. If the heart stops dead, the flow of blood completely stops. Then the cells of the brain, which need especially large amounts of oxygen, run short in just a few minutes and take devastating damage that never recovers, and die. The heart's continued beating is the most important life-support system, delivering the rations for living to the cells of the whole body." },
  { id:13, topic:"Rescuing a drowning person", emoji:"🆘",
    question:"You spot a friend or a person drowning in a river or the sea. To protect yourself while helping them, which is 'the thing you must absolutely never do'?",
    choices:["Shout loudly toward the adults around you, 'Someone come! A person is drowning!' and call for help","Think you can swim out and rescue them, and jump straight into the water empty-handed to grab the drowning person","Throw a rope, a long stick, or an empty plastic bottle (in place of a float) onto the water","Reach out a hand from solid ground nearby"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"A person who is drowning and cannot breathe is in complete panic from the fear of death. If a human swims close to help, the drowning person, with unbelievable, ferocious strength, clings to you from above your head to use you as a float, pushing you down under the water. When this happens, even an adult who is a good swimmer sinks to the bottom together with them, and the tragic accident of both people drowning happens endlessly around the world. If a person is drowning, it is absolutely forbidden to go into the water yourself. Shout loudly from a safe place on land and throw anything that floats - an empty bottle, a piece of wood - for them to grab. That is the correct survival code." },
  { id:14, topic:"Preventing tetanus", emoji:"🔩",
    question:"When you step on a rusty old nail, or get a deep wound from an old tool covered in soil, why must you never let your guard down even days later after the wound has closed?",
    choices:["The rusty iron turns into a magnet inside your skin","A germ called the tetanus bacterium, which loves places with no oxygen (air), can multiply deep in the wound and release a terrifying toxin that stiffens all the muscles of the body","Leaving a deep wound alone shortens the length of your leg years later","New fingernails grow out of the old wound"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Soil and old rusty iron hide the spores (like eggs) of the germ that causes 'tetanus.' The biggest feature of this germ is that it is 'anaerobic' - it hates touching air. So rather than a shallow surface wound, its favorite place is deep in a wound where air cannot reach, such as one made by a deep nail stab. After the wound closes, the germ multiplies explosively in the dark depths of the skin and releases an intense toxin that destroys the human nerves. Days to weeks later comes a terrifying illness in which the mouth can no longer open, or all the muscles arch backward and breathing becomes impossible. When you get a deep wound, you must have the wisdom to talk to a hospital about tetanus treatment." },
  { id:15, topic:"Strong light and the eyes", emoji:"👁️",
    question:"After staring directly at strong light - like sunlight or the fierce sparks of welding - why does the center of your vision keep flickering so you can't see, even after you close your eyes?",
    choices:["The strong light evaporated all the tears in your eyes","The cells of the most important screen deep in the eye that catches light (the retina) took heavy burn-like damage from too much energy, so the nerves are in a panic","Particles of light got trapped inside your eye and are rampaging in there","Your brain is remembering the color of the light"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Deep in the human eye is a very delicate screen of nerves called the 'retina,' which changes incoming light into electrical signals and sends them to the brain. Sunlight and very strong light contain energy with tremendous destructive power, such as ultraviolet rays. If you stare at this directly with your bare eyes, the same thing happens on your own retina as when a magnifying glass focuses sunlight to scorch paper. The flickering is proof that the cells are screaming because they are damaged. If this is severe, a hole opens in the center of the retina (solar retinopathy), leading to blindness, where your eyesight never returns. Turning your eyes away from strong light in one second is science's rule for protecting your eyes." },
  { id:16, topic:"Adult teeth", emoji:"🦷",
    question:"Why must you never let the adult teeth (the 'permanent teeth') that come in around the upper grades of elementary school get cavities - a reason that affects your whole life?",
    choices:["If an adult tooth gets a cavity, all the bones in your head become wobbly","Unlike baby teeth, once a permanent tooth gets a cavity and falls out, no new tooth will ever grow up from below - it is a part of the body that lasts a lifetime","Losing an adult tooth means you can no longer speak words at all","A tooth with a cavity starts moving on its own in the middle of the night"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Childhood teeth (baby teeth) are replaced even if they get cavities, as new adult teeth push up from below. But the 'permanent teeth' that come in around age 10 are literally the final version of teeth, made to be used until the very end of a human life. Unlike a lizard's tail or human skin, the hard enamel on the surface of a tooth, once it is destroyed and dissolved, will 100% never regenerate into its original shape by its own power. If you lose teeth, you can no longer chew food into small pieces, dealing major damage to your stomach and intestines, worsening your whole-body nutrition, and shortening your lifespan. Carefully protecting your adult teeth is providing for your own future health by yourself." },
  { id:17, topic:"Protecting the brain", emoji:"🚭",
    question:"Around the world, the law strictly forbids children and minors from putting 'alcohol,' 'tobacco,' or dangerous drugs that derange the brain into their bodies. What is the scientific reason?",
    choices:["Those things are a privilege for adults to enjoy alone","A child's body is still building the brain's neural circuits (network) at full speed until around age 20, and if poison enters, brain development stops completely and memory and emotional control are broken for life","If children use them, the color of all their clothes turns black","There is no real reason; it is just a rule adults made to restrict children"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The human brain spends the long time from birth until around age 20 doing daily construction work to wire up complex networks of nerve cells, so it can become wiser and better at controlling emotions. If poisons - alcohol, the nicotine in tobacco, or narcotics like cannabis - flow into the brain during this very delicate 'middle of construction' period, the brain's wiring work is destroyed into chaos and growth stops completely. As a result, even as an adult you can no longer think deeply, you snap and cause violent incidents, or you become a miserable body that cannot live without the drug (addiction). To protect your brain, hold a strong resolve to never go near these poisons your whole life." },
  { id:18, topic:"Sleep cleans the brain", emoji:"😴",
    question:"When you keep living without taking proper sleep every day, why do people become more likely to get sick and unable to think clearly?",
    choices:["If you don't sleep, the bones in your body get lighter and lighter and break","The cleaning system that washes out the harmful waste in the brain, and the growth hormone that heals the body's injuries - which work only while you sleep - stop working (the glymphatic system)","If you skip sleeping, the sun gets angry and gives off heat","If a human doesn't sleep, they completely transform into a robot in 3 days"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"During the day, while we live using our heads, the cells of the brain give off a lot of harmful protein waste, such as 'amyloid beta,' which builds up inside the head. When a person enters deep sleep at night, the brain cells shrink a little to make gaps, and into those gaps cerebrospinal fluid - clean water - flows in like a tidal wave, beginning a great cleaning that washes away the day's waste all at once. This is the brain's cleaning system discovered in recent medicine. If you keep getting too little sleep, poisonous waste stays piled up in your head, the nerves die and you get irritable, your immunity drops, and you lose to every kind of illness. Sleep is the best detergent for the brain." },
  { id:19, topic:"How heredity works", emoji:"🧬",
    question:"In every country of the world, and throughout ancient history, there has been a rule against marrying and having children with very close blood relatives (parent and child, brother and sister). What is the common scientific (genetic) reason?",
    choices:["With close relatives, the name of the child to be born cannot be decided","Everyone carries a small mistake in their blueprint (a cause of illness) somewhere in their genes, and between close relatives the same mistakes overlap, so the chance of a child born with a serious illness or disability shoots up","With close relatives, the inside of the house gets cramped","God dislikes that kind of appearance"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The genes that are the blueprint of the human body are made by receiving a set of two volumes - half from the father and half from the mother. Everyone secretly carries a few serious blueprint mistakes somewhere in one volume, but if the other volume's blueprint is normal, you can live healthily without getting sick. However, humans who are close blood relatives inherit their blueprints from exactly the same ancestors, so the locations of their mistakes are very similar. When these two people have a child, a blueprint with a bug in exactly the same place from both father and mother lines up in a double, the mistake can no longer be covered, and a baby with a serious illness or disability is born. From experience and wisdom, humankind has made the rule to avoid this risk." },
  { id:20, topic:"Blood transfusion and types", emoji:"🩸",
    question:"Why must you never, on an amateur's judgment, pour your own 'blood' straight into a badly injured person's body with an injection to share it (a transfusion)?",
    choices:["If another person's blood enters, the color of your hair becomes the same as theirs","Blood has types (A, B, O, AB), and if different types mix, the red blood cells violently reject each other inside the body, clump together, clog the blood vessels, and kill the person","Sharing blood cuts your own body weight in half","Drinking another person's blood gives you a stomachache"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Blood all looks like the same red liquid, but the surface of the red blood cells has 'antigens' - special marks (keys and stamps) that show the type of that blood. This is the blood type (the ABO system). For example, if you mistakenly pour B-type blood into the body of a type-A person, the type-A person's immune team panics - 'an enemy I have never seen has invaded!' - and attacks all the incoming type-B red blood cells at once, tangling them into a tight clump like a net (an agglutination reaction). The clumped blood clogs the thick blood vessels of the lungs and brain and causes shock death in an instant. In medicine, the test that checks the blood type is a confirmation of life that can never be skipped." },
  { id:21, topic:"Chewing well", emoji:"🍽️",
    question:"When you put food in your mouth, why does chewing well with your teeth (chewing over 30 times) before swallowing dramatically help the work of your stomach and intestines?",
    choices:["If you chew well, the food completely vanishes inside your mouth","Grinding the food into small pieces widens the total 'surface area' many times over, so the digestive juices in your gut soak in quickly across the whole thing and absorb the nutrients efficiently","Chewing raises the temperature inside your stomach to 100 degrees","Training your teeth makes the muscles in the soles of your feet stronger"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a wonderful application of the math idea of 'surface area.' If you toss a big lump of potato into your stomach as it is, the stomach acid (the acid of digestion) can only dissolve it from the surface, so it takes many hours to dissolve to the center, the stomach gets tired, and you upset your gut. But if you use your teeth to chew it into fine crumbs, one big lump splits into thousands of tiny pieces. By splitting into pieces, the total area where the food can touch the digestive juices widens explosively. Thanks to this, the moment it reaches the stomach and intestines, the digestive juices soak through to the center in an instant, dissolve the food into a mush, and absorb 100% of the nutrients for living, leaving none behind. Chewing well is the very first cooking factory, before the gut." },
  { id:22, topic:"Choking (life-saving)", emoji:"🍖",
    question:"When a large piece of food gets stuck in someone's throat and they are choking, you hug them from behind and thrust upward hard on their belly (the Heimlich maneuver). What is the real purpose of pushing on the belly?",
    choices:["To dent the belly so they look slimmer","Pressing the belly hard pushes up the air still left in the lungs, and with that air pressure (the force of an air gun) it blows the object stuck in the throat out forcefully","To startle the worms inside the belly","To force the stuck food down into the stomach"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"When something is stuck in the throat and a person can't breathe, there is actually still plenty of unexhaled air left inside the lungs. Between the human chest and belly is a large muscle floor called the 'diaphragm,' which inflates and shrinks the lungs. When you hug from behind and thrust hard upward just above the navel, the organs in the belly are pushed up, and in turn the diaphragm slams the lungs hard from below. Then the air left in the lungs reverses toward the throat in an instant like a fierce storm and, just like an air gun, flicks out the lump of food that was blocking the throat. It is a wonderful, physics-based life-saving technique that uses the structure of the human body." },
  { id:23, topic:"Parasites and raw food", emoji:"🐛",
    question:"Why must you never eat raw meat from wild animals, or drink raw water from a river, without heating it - a terrifying reason about worms breeding inside your body?",
    choices:["Eating raw food transforms a human's body into an animal","Inside creatures' bodies and raw water lurk parasites - hidden as invisible eggs - that get into the human intestine, bite the wall, and steal nutrients or devour the organs","Raw water turns all the bones in your belly to mush","Eating raw meat makes animal cries echo inside your belly"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"River water in nature, and the meat of wild deer, boar, or pigs, almost 100% hide the eggs and larvae of tiny invisible 'parasites' (such as tapeworms and roundworms). If you eat these raw, they survive even the acid in your stomach and reach the intestine in your belly. There the eggs hatch, and the long ones grow into giant worms several meters long that cling to the intestine wall and suck away all the nutrients you ate to live, leaving you malnourished. Some burrow into the brain or liver and dissolve the organs into mush - vicious worms that threaten your life. Parasites are very weak to fire (heat), so the wisdom of hygiene is absolutely needed: cook meat thoroughly to the center, and boil water to wipe them all out." },
  { id:24, topic:"Finish your medicine", emoji:"💊",
    question:"When you take 'antibiotics' from the doctor that kill the germs inside your body, what is the terrifying rule of medicine you must absolutely keep?",
    choices:["Once your fever drops and you feel better, stop taking it right away on your own judgment because the medicine is precious","Even if the symptoms ease and it seems cured, take all of it to the very end, for the number of days instructed, until the germs in your body reach zero","Change the time you take the medicine to a different random time every day on a whim","If a friend has a cold, share your leftover medicine with them"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"When you start taking antibiotics, first the weak, common, low-level germs inside your body die off in order. After about half die, the human body feels as if it has fully recovered. If you stop taking it here, thinking 'I'm cured,' the few most vicious, stubborn germs that endured the medicine's attack and were still barely surviving come back to life and start breeding massively again in your belly. Because these newly increased germs once experienced the medicine's attack and survived, they have transformed into monster germs (drug-resistant bacteria) carrying a super-strong barrier the medicine can no longer beat. Now, even taking the same medicine has no effect at all, there is no treatment left, and it leads to death. Keep taking the medicine without easing up until they are completely wiped out - this is the iron rule of medicine that protects the world." },
  { id:25, topic:"How frostbite works", emoji:"🥶",
    question:"When you stay a long time in an extremely freezing place, such as a snowy mountain or on ice, why do your fingers and toes turn purple and lose feeling ('frostbite')?",
    choices:["The cold wind paints the surface of your skin purple","To protect the temperature of the most important heart and organs (the body's center), the brain narrows the blood vessels in the fingers and toes and gathers the blood only in the center","In a cold place, all the blood in your body freezes at once and stops moving","Your fingers and toes fell asleep from the cold"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the evidence of a cruel but ultimate defense system for surviving that the human brain has. When the whole body is exposed to freezing extreme cold, if blood kept flowing as usual all the way to the fingertips, the blood cooled there would return to the heart, dropping the temperature of the heart and brain (the core temperature) and causing instant death by freezing. To prevent this, the brain orders: 'Sacrifice the fingertips if you must, but never let the central heart's flame of life go out!' Then the blood vessels of the hands and feet clamp tightly shut and blood stops reaching them. The fingertips, which no longer receive blood (oxygen), have cells that die and turn purple, and in the worst case rot and drop off (frostbite). In cold places, keep moving your hands and feet, change wet gloves right away, and keep the brain from giving the order to give up the hands and feet." },
  { id:26, topic:"Darkness and the eyes", emoji:"🌙",
    question:"The moment you enter a pitch-dark room with no electricity at night, you can't see anything, but if you stand still there for about 10 minutes, the shapes of the furniture and walls around you faintly come into view. Why?",
    choices:["An invisible beam of light automatically starts firing from the human eye","The black hole in the center of the eye (the pupil) opens wide in the dark and changes shape to gather as much of the faint light around it (like starlight) as possible (dark adaptation)","The brain freely imagines the dark scenery and projects an illusion","As time passes, the color of the night's darkness gets lighter"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The black hole in the center of the human eye is called the 'pupil,' and like the aperture of a camera lens, it has a muscle curtain that automatically adjusts the amount of light entering the eye. In a bright place, like under the sun, the pupil shrinks as small as the tip of a needle so too much light won't burn the eye. When you suddenly move to a pitch-dark place, at first there isn't enough light and it looks completely black. But over about 10 minutes, this pupil curtain opens to its limit, and it begins desperately gathering the faint specks of light in the corners of the room that are too thin to see. This system is called 'dark adaptation.' Even in a pinch in the dark, don't panic - by closing your eyes and waiting still for 10 minutes, you can regain the compass of your sight. It is the wisdom of the human body." },
  { id:27, topic:"The science of layering", emoji:"🧥",
    question:"When dressing warmly in a very cold season, why is it far warmer to wear many thin layers (layering) than to wear just one thick, big piece of clothing?",
    choices:["More pieces of clothing make the clothes heavier so they suck up heat from the ground","Between layer and layer, many still-air layers (insulation) - the slowest thing on Earth at conducting heat - are made, completely blocking your body heat from escaping outside","When many thin clothes rub together, a fire breaks out inside","Wearing many clothes makes the wind go around and avoid them"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This too is wonderful science wisdom that uses the properties of matter. The strongest material in the world at being hard to conduct heat (at blocking heat) is actually still air (gas). Even if you wear just one thick piece of clothing, the warm body heat inside travels through the fibers of the cloth and escapes outside. But if you layer 3 or 4 thin pieces, many rooms of air completely trapped and unable to move form in the gaps between the clothes. This layer of air acts as insulation, just like the wall of a thermos, becoming the strongest barrier that won't let your warm 36-degree body heat escape and won't let the freezing cold air in. When you have no clothes, even stuffing dry newspaper or fallen leaves into your clothing makes the same air layer and can protect your life from freezing to death." },
  { id:28, topic:"Fight-or-flight", emoji:"🏃",
    question:"When a ferocious carnivore suddenly appears in front of you, or you meet a huge crisis, why does your heart suddenly pound hard and you break into a cold sweat, regardless of your own will?",
    choices:["It is a sign the heart is panicking with fear, breaking down and about to fail","To survive, the brain starts preparing to fight right now or dash away at full power, explosively sending huge amounts of oxygen (blood) to the muscles of the whole body (the fight-or-flight response)","When in a crisis, the amount of blood in your body doubles","To make the heart loud so it startles the enemy in front and makes them faint"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"When a human feels desperate fear or crisis, the emergency command center deep in the brain (the amygdala) senses the danger in an instant and releases a flood of a special hormone called adrenaline into the blood. The moment this hormone arrives, the heart's pump switches to ultra-high-speed full-power operation, raising the pulse with a pounding beat, and rushes huge amounts of oxygen (blood) to the muscles of the legs and arms for fighting or running away. At the same time, it shrinks the blood vessels of the skin to keep bleeding to a minimum if you get injured, so your face goes pale and you break into a cold sweat. In the language of medicine this is called the 'fight-or-flight response.' Your heart pounding is the finest defense sign that your body, to protect you, has released all its energy and transformed into battle mode." },
  { id:29, topic:"The role of vitamins", emoji:"🍊",
    question:"Even if you fill your belly every day with lots of rice and potatoes, why do you get sick (such as scurvy), with blood bursting from blood vessels all over the body, if you eat no fresh vegetables or fruit at all for months?",
    choices:["If you don't eat vegetables, all the red color in your blood disappears","The three major nutrients (like carbohydrates) alone are not enough; vitamins - which act as the glue that firmly sticks cells together and the lubricant that helps chemical reactions - run dry","The body of a person who doesn't eat fruit has a rule that worms devour it from inside","Your stomach stops working if it doesn't see the green color of vegetables"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"A human can get fat eating rice and bread (carbohydrates), but that alone absolutely cannot keep you healthy. To keep the trillions of cells and the walls of the blood vessels in the body in a springy, healthy state, you absolutely need 'vitamins' (especially vitamin C and others) - micronutrients the body cannot make on its own. Vitamins are essential parts for making 'collagen (the glue of cells)' that builds the body. If these run short for months, the glue of cells all over the body snaps to pieces, the tiny blood vessels of the gums, skin, and organs everywhere tear, and blood slowly leaks from inside - the terrifying illness 'scurvy' - and in the end you die. Not just filling your belly, but taking in tiny amounts of vitamins and minerals, is the truth of nutrition that keeps the system of life going." },
  { id:30, topic:"Fever is a defense", emoji:"🤒",
    question:"When cold or infection germs enter your body, your body shivers and a high fever over 38 degrees appears. Why must you not force the fever down with medicine right away - a medical reason?",
    choices:["Lowering the fever suddenly turns all the water in your body into hot water","Fever is a correct defense response - the brain deliberately raises body temperature so the immune team can fight best and to stop the breeding of germs and viruses, which are weak to heat","Lowering the fever makes all the hair on your head fall out","When you have a high fever, your running speed gets faster"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Congratulations! With this, the first 30 questions of 'Wise World 3' are complete. Many people misunderstand fever as a bad thing to lower right away, but that is a big mistake. Many germs and viruses that invade the body love the human normal temperature of around 36 degrees best, and multiply most explosively there. But when the temperature rises to 38-39 degrees, the virus's movement is paralyzed and it can no longer multiply. On the other hand, our immune team, such as the white blood cells, moves many times more energetically and quickly when body temperature is high. In other words, a fever is the brain's strategy of deliberately turning up the room temperature to gain the advantage in battle. Cooling your head, taking in plenty of fluids, and watching over the fever your body is fighting with - without forcing it down - and resting, is the finest survival-medicine wisdom for not letting it become a serious illness." },
  { id:31, topic:"Division of labor", emoji:"🛠️",
    question:"When the adults of a society don't all do the same job, but split into different jobs like farmer, carpenter, and doctor ('division of labor'), what is the greatest benefit?",
    choices:["If everyone did the same job, it would be hard to remember each other's faces","It removes the time limit of one person having to learn every tool and skill from scratch, and when each specialist cooperates, the productivity of the whole society explodes upward","Doing division of labor doubles the working hours every day","More kinds of jobs make things look livelier and more fun"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"If there were no division of labor, you would have to grow your own wheat to eat, build your own house to live in, and make your own medicine when you got sick. There would never be enough hours in a day, everything would be half-finished, and living a rich life would be impossible. Humankind invented the greatest wisdom of 'division of labor,' where each person concentrates on one job and masters its skill, and they exchange the goods and services they make. This lets us produce many times more high-quality results with less effort, and forms a rich society where we support each other's lives with the highest efficiency." },
  { id:32, topic:"Money is trust", emoji:"💵",
    question:"The paper bills (currency) we use every day are just scraps of paper, so why can we use them to exchange for delicious food and fine tools?",
    choices:["Inside that paper is a magic ingredient that fills your stomach","Because everyone in society places a shared 'trust' in that bill - that 'if I hand over this paper, I can always exchange it for goods of the same value'","Because the law says the design on the bill is the most beautiful in the world","Because the weight of the paper is about the same as a lump of iron"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The true nature of money (currency) is not its value as a material, but a 'system of trust' between people. Long ago people exchanged gold and silver themselves, but they were heavy and inconvenient to carry, so countries and societies created a shared paper tool called the 'bill,' whose trust they guarantee. Because the promise and trust in everyone's heads agree - 'even if I accept a bill, I can use it the same way at the next shop' - a mere scrap of paper holds the powerful ability to be exchanged for goods. In a society where trust has collapsed, bills literally turn into worthless scraps." },
  { id:33, topic:"A measure of value", emoji:"📏",
    question:"Compared to a life of barter, what convenient and fair system was born by putting 'money (currency)' in the middle of buying and selling?",
    choices:["Using money makes the weight of all goods drop to half","The value of all goods can be expressed with a shared ruler called 'numbers,' so even different kinds of goods can always be compared fairly by price and traded (a measure of value)","Using money means the shopkeeper always gives you a bonus","The time a trade takes always becomes exactly 1 second"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Money has the important role of a 'measure of value,' measuring the value of all goods in numbers. In a world of barter with no money, you would have to discuss with the other person every time - 'how many fish is this one sheep worth, how many bags of wheat, how many axes?' - and the calculation would become a mess. But once money, a shared ruler, appeared in the middle, you could compare everything with the same numbers, like 'a sheep is 10,000 coins, a fish is 500 coins.' This let everyone trade fairly and smoothly, without confusion and without losing out." },
  { id:34, topic:"A store of value", emoji:"💰",
    question:"When you get a lot of food like fish and vegetables, why is it better to change it into 'money (currency)' once and save it, rather than keeping it as it is?",
    choices:["Saving money makes energy spring up from inside your body on its own","Food rots in a few days and its value becomes zero, but by changing it into money you can 'store the fruit of your labor for years without letting it rot' (a store of value)","Changing it into money doubles the amount of food","If you put money in your pocket, it automatically shines"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The third great function of money is the 'store of value.' Even if you work hard and harvest a huge amount of fish or bananas, if you leave them as they are they rot in a few days, and the crystal of your effort vanishes. That way you cannot store wealth for future crises (famine or injury). But by quickly converting what you harvested into money, a 'tool that does not rot,' you can keep the value you worked for, exactly, like a time capsule, even ten years ahead. Money is a safe storehouse for protecting your future self." },
  { id:35, topic:"Transfer of value", emoji:"👛",
    question:"In trade, instead of carrying heavy potatoes or cattle as they are, what is the wonderful benefit, from the viewpoint of movement, of trading using 'money (currency)'?",
    choices:["Holding money lets your legs run twice as fast","You can put it in a small wallet or pocket and 'carry the value of your property lightly to any far-off place' (transfer of value)","Money floats on water, so you can swim across the sea","Going far away makes money's value increase on its own"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Money has the function of 'transfer of value.' If you want to go to a far town and buy a rare medicine or a sturdy tool, without money you would have to drag heavy crops or a cattle ox on foot for days. The risk of being attacked by thieves along the way or the ox dying is very high. But if you change that wealth once into a light, small form - bills or coins - you can hide it in a wallet and safely carry an enormous value to a far land in an instant and trade. It is powerful infrastructure for an economy to cross borders." },
  { id:36, topic:"The contract", emoji:"📝",
    question:"When you make a work promise with someone, or buy and sell goods, why must you always leave a written 'contract' on paper, not just a verbal promise?",
    choices:["Writing many contracts trains your hand muscles and makes you strong","Human memory becomes vague and changes over time, so fixing the promise's content in writing prevents later quarrels of 'you said, you didn't' and being deceived, protecting yourself","A promise written in words is automatically granted by God with magic","Holding a paper document makes you look important"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"One of the most important documents for surviving in society is the 'contract.' No matter how close a friend or how trustworthy an adult may seem, you must not settle a promise like 'I will pay this much money in a few months' or 'I will finish this job by then' with words alone. Over time, someone will surely appear who conveniently rewrites their memory or lies to wriggle out of it. By leaving written evidence with each other's signatures and seals, even if the other party breaks the promise, you can borrow the power of surrounding adults or the law and protect yourself rightfully. A contract is a bulletproof vest for walking safely in the adult world." },
  { id:37, topic:"Supply and demand", emoji:"⚖️",
    question:"In the market, the harvest of a certain bean dropped sharply because of heavy rain, and the number of beans in the world became very small. But the number of people who want them is large. At this time, how does the price of beans change?",
    choices:["Since there are few and no one can buy them, the price becomes zero","It becomes a scramble among people who want them, and more people are willing to pay even higher money to buy, so the price of beans 'rises sharply'","No matter what, the price of all goods is always constant everywhere in the world","The beans grow bigger in shape, and the price drops a little"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the absolute law that is the most basic of economics: 'demand (the amount wanted) and supply (the amount sold).' The price of goods is not decided by someone's whim, but automatically by the balance (scale) of these two. When the number of people who want to buy (demand) becomes overwhelmingly larger than the number of goods to sell (supply), the value of the goods (scarcity value) shoots up. If you know this system, you can calmly read ahead - 'what is short now, and what is being sought' - and make a business plan that smartly solves society's troubles." },
  { id:38, topic:"What profit means", emoji:"📈",
    question:"What is the true, essential meaning in society of making a 'profit (earnings)' by doing business?",
    choices:["To deceive others and take it easy and live in luxury just for yourself","As a result of solving what others are troubled by (inconvenience or worry) with your own wisdom and labor, to rightfully receive value beyond the cost you spent (the purchase cost), as 'the reward for your thanks and usefulness'","To get money from the country on your own and put it in your pocket","To make your shop's name the most famous in the world"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Making a profit in business is never a bad thing, nor squeezing money out of someone. Profit is calculated as '(selling price) minus (purchase cost or the cost to make it).' For example, suppose for someone who can't go to a clean spring far away, you carry a bucket and draw water for them, and share water you bought for 10 coins at 20 coins. The 10-coin profit of this difference is a rightful reward of thanks for resolving their 'inconvenience of travel.' The more you solve someone's pain in society, the more the trust called profit gathers in your hands." },
  { id:39, topic:"What banks do", emoji:"🏦",
    question:"What was the most fundamental purpose for which the place born long ago called the 'bank' was valued by people in society and developed?",
    choices:["To decorate a room with many beautiful bills and gaze at them","Because keeping a lot of money at home risks being stolen by thieves, to have it 'safely stored (deposit)' in a sturdy vault, and to make safe transfers (payments) to far-off towns","Depositing money automatically makes the bill's size bigger","To announce to everyone who has the most money and boast"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The first purpose for which banks were born was the 'need for safe storage.' Keeping gold coins or a lot of bills in your own home carries the big risk of them burning in a fire, or of being attacked by robbers and even losing your life. So people created a system to 'deposit' money in the place with the sturdiest vault and guards in society. If you deposit money in a bank, it becomes a record of numbers in a passbook, and you can protect your precious property 100% from theft. It is a base of wisdom that safely manages money not as a 'physical lump of paper' but as 'trusted numbers.'" },
  { id:40, topic:"Debt and interest", emoji:"💸",
    question:"When you 'borrow money (debt)' from another person or a bank, what is the frightening economic mechanism you must never forget?",
    choices:["Borrowing money makes your height shrink a little","Not only must you return the borrowed money (the principal) as is, but in place of the time you borrowed it, you must always add extra money (interest) on top and return more","A rule that once you borrow money, you may never shop again","That borrowed money may be kept as your own without returning it"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Borrowing money is 'borrowing in advance' from your future self's labor and freedom. Debt always carries a rental fee called 'interest' or 'rate.' For example, if you borrow 10,000 coins and the interest rule is 10%, you must return 11,000 coins later. If you take this interest mechanism lightly, no matter how much you pay back, the interest calculation keeps swelling (like a snowball), and you end up a slave-like life paying money for others your whole life. Unless you have a sure plan to grow money, you should absolutely avoid easy debt." },
  { id:41, topic:"Investment vs spending", emoji:"🌱",
    question:"There are two ways to use money. In contrast to 'spending,' buying sweets you eat now that disappear right away, which is a concrete example of 'investment,' using money to grow your future power and wealth?",
    choices:["Buying lots of the latest fashionable, flashy clothes","Buying a sturdy 'tool' to start a new job of your own, or using money on 'books (study)' to gain knowledge","Pouring all the money you have into casino or game gambling","Putting money on a plate and just staring at it"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"If you only use money (spending/wasting), money simply vanishes from your hands and that's it. But a wise person uses money as a 'seed (investment) to multiply their own future power.' For example, if a person who whittled wood by hand saves money and buys a high-performance axe (tool), from the next day they can make 10 times the firewood in the same time, and the money coming in increases dramatically. Also, buying and studying books on medicine or science is the strongest 'self-investment,' turning your own brain into the best money-earning tool. Move by calculating what to spend money on to make your future rich." },
  { id:42, topic:"Taxes and public goods", emoji:"🌉",
    question:"Why is a system absolutely necessary where everyone in a village or town puts out a little of the money they earn - 'taxes' or collected money (community funds)?",
    choices:["To use the pooled money to hold a big festival every day with everyone","To maintain, with everyone, the 'shared well, sturdy roads, big bridges, and hospitals that help the sick (public goods)' that one person's money could never make, and protect society","To gather a lot of money and bury it deep underground","To make a certain great leader's house luxurious like a castle"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"If society had no taxes or money put out together (public funds) at all, no one alone could pay enormous money to build a big bridge or pave long roads. If roads are in ruins, no one can move for fear of injury, and business and life completely collapse. That is exactly why everyone puts out a little money each and pools it, to build and maintain 'shared infrastructure no one can make alone (public goods).' This system of supporting each other (social security and public assistance) is the very base of welfare that protects the world's safety." },
  { id:43, topic:"The value of work", emoji:"💪",
    question:"What is the essential, greatest value as a human of 'working (laboring)' in society?",
    choices:["Being ordered by someone and just moving your body like a robot","Using your wonderful energy of 'time, skill, and wisdom' to solve someone's 'inconvenience or trouble (pain)' in society and make the world better than yesterday","Working more hours than others, breaking your body, and boasting","Getting a license to do anything as long as you get money"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The true form of working is not simply a task to get money. It is an action of value creation, offering your precious time of life and skills to society and turning someone's 'I'm in trouble!' into 'That's great!' A farmer making delicious food erases hunger, and a doctor giving treatment erases pain. Through working, you are needed within society and become an important piece of the puzzle that supports someone's life. Knowing the purpose of work correctly strengthens the pride and the legs of independence of your life." },
  { id:44, topic:"The danger of monopoly", emoji:"👑",
    question:"When there is 'only one shop' selling a certain important medicine in the market (monopoly), why is it very dangerous for the buyer?",
    choices:["With only one shop, it becomes a bother to remember the shop's name","Because there is no rival to compete, even if the shopkeeper unfairly jacks the price up to a 'tremendously high price,' the buyer has no choice but to pay that high money to live","With one shop, the medicine's shape automatically turns into a triangle","There is no danger; one shop is always safer"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"A state with no rivals at all in the market is called 'monopoly.' When a monopoly happens, the beautiful scale of supply and demand breaks, and the seller can freely control the price like a god. Even if a medicine that should sell for 10 coins is told to you as 'It's 10,000 coins. If you don't like it, don't buy it and get sick,' exploitation happens where your entire fortune is taken to live. That is exactly why a healthy society protects the system of 'competition,' where several shops sell similar goods and compete, and puts up a barrier so prices don't become unfairly high." },
  { id:45, topic:"The too-good-to-be-true trap", emoji:"🎣",
    question:"A stranger adult gave you a sweet invitation: 'If you help me with this job, I'll give you a huge sum of money you've never seen, in an instant.' What should you do?",
    choices:["Since it's a chance to get a big sum, help right away without thinking","Absolutely refuse and leave the place. In this world, a 'job with no risk where you easily get a huge sum' 100% never exists; it is a trap to make you carry part of a crime and destroy your life","Invite lots of friends and do the job together with everyone","Make a paper contract on the spot for how much you'll get"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The cold, absolute rule of economics is that 'the size of the reward (money you get) is fully proportional to the size of the value you provided and the size of the risk you bear.' Behind a story of giving a child with no special skill a huge sum in an instant, there is 100% a vicious criminal trap - 'transporting drugs' or being a 'collector for a scam that deceives people and takes their money' - that gets you caught by the police in one shot and completely ends your life. The wisdom to be wary with the eye of logic of people who approach with sweet words, and to flatly refuse, protects your freedom for life." },
  { id:46, topic:"Inflation", emoji:"🎈",
    question:"When 'the total amount of money' circulating in the world is printed in too-large quantities between countries and banks and increases too much, what happens to the prices of the whole society (the prices of goods)?",
    choices:["Since money increased a lot, the price of all goods drops to 1 coin","Because money's scarcity value (rarity) falls and it nears a scrap of paper, relatively 'the price of all goods rises sharply (inflation)'","Even if the amount of money changes, the price of goods never changes on Earth","Goods start transforming into the shape of bills"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the mechanism of 'inflation,' a dynamic disease of the economy. What would happen if a country printed bills infinitely and handed them to everyone? Because everyone holds lots of money, now a scramble for 'goods' happens. Then a terrifying phenomenon occurs where bread you could buy for 100 coins yesterday can't be bought the next day without 10,000 coins, and the day after without 1,000,000 coins. Money's value crashes, and the power of money you carefully saved becomes garbage in an instant. Knowing the balance of money's 'amount' and goods' 'number' gives you a big-picture view of the world." },
  { id:47, topic:"The buy-now-pay-later trap", emoji:"💳",
    question:"What is the hidden greatest trap of the system (credit) where 'I don't have money now, but if I show this card (or make a promise), I can shop right now and pay next month'?",
    choices:["When next month comes, the tool you bought disappears on its own","Because money doesn't decrease from your wallet right now, your sense of how poor you are becoming right now is numbed, and you end up carrying a debt your future self can absolutely never pay","If you lose the card, your name changes completely","The moment you shop, your whole body's weight doubles"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Credit cards and tabs (credit trading) are very convenient tools, but they are also a dangerous trap that strikes a weak point of the human brain. When 'bills' physically decrease from a wallet, a human feels strong pain (the fear of losing) and can brake, but with a promise of numbers (paying later), the brain feels no pain at all. So you blithely spend up 'the money your future self is supposed to work hard to earn.' When next month comes and you can't pay, interest is added and you go bankrupt in an instant. Living within the range of the cash at hand is the basis of economic independence." },
  { id:48, topic:"Opportunity cost", emoji:"⏳",
    question:"You have '1 hour' of time, or '1,000 coins' of money. When you choose what to do with it, what does the economic concept you must never forget, 'opportunity cost,' mean?",
    choices:["A special fee you must pay to the country each time you shop","Choosing one option means at the same time that 'you are giving up and throwing away another wonderful chance or value you could have gotten if you hadn't chosen it' (a trade-off)","A system where using a tool for a long time automatically increases its value","It means that time you spend sleeping at home doing nothing costs no money at all"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Our resources, like time and money, are 'completely finite (have limits)' for everyone in the world. If you buy a game with 1,000 coins, the chance to buy a study book with that 1,000 coins is gone forever. If you spend 1 hour on play, the chance to use that 1 hour on work or study is gone. This 'other greatest value you are secretly sacrificing behind the scenes by choosing something' is called 'opportunity cost.' A wise person who knows this, when deciding something, weighs 'by doing this, what am I losing instead?' and can make the least-bad choice." },
  { id:49, topic:"Pooling together", emoji:"🤝",
    question:"When a village's farmers really want to use a 'huge farming machine (tractor)' that's too expensive for one person to ever buy, what is the wisest economic wisdom to obtain it by joining forces?",
    choices:["Pray every day and wait for someone to become rich and buy it as a gift for you","Everyone puts out a little money and pools it (a cooperative), buys one machine as everyone's shared tool, and uses it in turns by a fair schedule","Sneak into another town's field at midnight and steal the machine quietly","Give up buying the machine and have everyone do it by hand for a lifetime"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Even if one person's capital (the money they have) is small, when many people gather with the same purpose and put out money to make one powerful lump, this economic system that solves a huge problem is called the wisdom of 'cooperation' or 'microfinance.' If you use a machine bought with the pooled money, everyone's field harvest increases many times over, and more money than you put out returns to everyone. Rather than depending on a strong rich person, weak people decide rules as equals, put out funds together, and self-sufficiently produce wealth on their own - the most beautiful system of an economic sphere." },
  { id:50, topic:"An equal trade", emoji:"🛒",
    question:"When you shop and pay money, which is the correct relationship as humans between the 'paying side (buyer)' and the 'selling side (seller)' who receives the bill and hands over the goods?",
    choices:["The paying customer is great like a god, so it's fine to bully the clerk","The seller offers 'goods of wonderful value' and the buyer offers 'trusted money of the same value' - they are 'completely equal partners' based on mutual agreement","The shop that sells goods is greater, so the buyer should always grovel and obey","Which is greater is decided by the weather that day"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"A very common, ugly mistake in society is the misunderstanding that 'the paying side gets to put on airs.' Business is not an up-down of power, but an 'equal, equivalent exchange' of each other's value. Without the convenient tool the seller worked hard to make, your 100-coin piece stays a mere lump of metal. Conversely, without your money, the clerk can't buy other things. Each paying respect to the other - 'thank you for selling,' 'thank you for buying' - is the lubricant of society and the best foundation for keeping a gentle economic sphere turning." },
  { id:51, topic:"Seeing through ads", emoji:"📺",
    question:"You saw an 'advertisement (a commercial)' on TV, the internet, billboards, etc., appealing a product as tremendously attractive. What should you be careful of when you see this?",
    choices:["What the ad says is 100% absolute truth, so you should believe it all and buy right away","Because the ad's purpose is 'to make you spend money so they make a profit,' doubt the beautifully decorated looks and words once, and calmly calculate whether it has essential value you truly need","When you see an ad, tell all your friends 'if you don't buy this you'll get sick'","Everyone appearing in ads is a bad person, so you should always get angry"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The techniques of advertising and marketing are made to thoroughly research the human feelings of 'I want it!' and 'everyone has it so I want to boast too!' (a weak point of psychology), to make you open your wallet. Even if a cute character or a famous person says 'it's the best,' that is merely a line they say after getting ad money. A person who swallows media information as is (lacking media literacy) is made to dance for others' profit their whole life, and has their wallet emptied. Hold the cleverness to see through the 'purpose behind' information." },
  { id:52, topic:"How insurance works", emoji:"🛡️",
    question:"What do we call the world-shared mutual-aid system where, against a huge misfortune crisis like 'a serious injury, serious illness, or a big house fire' that no one knows when or to whom it will happen, everyone puts out a little money to prepare?",
    choices:["Shopping","Insurance (mutual aid)","Monopoly","Savings"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"If you live all alone and suddenly get a serious illness needing millions of coins in medical fees, you can't pay and lose your life just like that. So humankind invented 'insurance,' an economic shield that gently saves each other. From while healthy, many people put out small money - like 100 coins each month - into one big vault and save it. Then when one member among them unfortunately gets a serious injury, that vault pays out a large amount of money to cover the treatment cost. It is humankind's most beautiful wisdom of spreading risk: 'one for all, all for one.'" },
  { id:53, topic:"Overfishing and sustainability", emoji:"🐟",
    question:"A fisherman, saying 'if I catch a lot now I can make a big profit,' caught up all the fish in the sea every day at once, leaving none, down to the small baby fish (overfishing). Why will this business surely fail in a few years and starve?",
    choices:["Catching too many fish makes the sea god angry and turns all the bills into sand","Natural resources (plants and animals) have a 'speed of regeneration' of birthing children and increasing, and if you exceed it and drive them extinct, what you sell in the future completely vanishes (collapse of sustainability)","Catching too many fish makes them so heavy that the boat floats into the sky","When the number of fish drops, the sea water's temperature rises to 100 degrees and is dangerous"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"A concept you can never ignore to keep an economy lasting forever is 'sustainability.' Earth's natural blessings are not an infinitely gushing spring. The great principle is to use fish and forest trees within the range of the speed at which they naturally increase, as if receiving a little 'interest.' A foolish businessperson who can only think of immediate profit destroys nature, the foundation, with their own hands, and in a few years starves everyone and self-destructs. Hold the big-picture view to live wisely while leaving resources for the children of the future." },
  { id:54, topic:"Rare skills", emoji:"🧠",
    question:"A person who gets a lot of 'salary (reward)' for their work in society is not simply someone big-bodied or someone who puts on airs, but a person with what quality?",
    choices:["A person who shouts louder than anyone every day to give them money","A person who has 'special knowledge, high skill, deep experience' that no one else can easily imitate, and who can solve society's big troubles (a rare talent)","A person who is the best in the world at slacking off work hours","A person who doesn't step out of the house every day and just sleeps still"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The rule deciding the amount of salary also actually moves according to the law of 'supply and demand.' Easy work anyone can imitate in 1 second has tens of thousands of people worldwide who can do it instead, so the salary is low. But a person with 'specialist knowledge (skill)' gained through long years of study and effort - like 'I can operate on and cure this hard illness' or 'I can develop a convenient system no one can make' - becomes a 'rare, high-value talent' with no replacement in the world. If you want to receive a lot of money, the right answer is not to shout loudly, but to polish your head and skill and become a one-and-only existence that society seeks." },
  { id:55, topic:"The benefit of competition", emoji:"🏁",
    question:"On the same street, two shops selling meat appeared, 'Shop A' and 'Shop B' (competition). What wonderful benefit does these two shops competing bring to the buyers (citizens)?",
    choices:["With two shops, the meat's taste automatically turns into chocolate flavor","To get the buyer to choose their shop, each desperately starts to devise 'let's make the price cheaper' and 'let's make the meat fresher and tastier'","The two shops have a fierce fistfight every day, and you can watch it","Buying meat always takes twice as long"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Rivals selling the same product in the market competing is called 'competition.' With competition, shopkeepers can't slack off. If Shop A sold bad meat at a high price, all the customers would go to Shop B, and Shop A would go bankrupt. That is exactly why each desperately uses their head and repeats devising 'how can I deliver cheaper, better things to everyone.' This energy of competition is the engine that keeps evolving the whole society's technology, medicine, and quality of service more and more every day." },
  { id:56, topic:"Improving productivity", emoji:"🚜",
    question:"What do we call, in economic terms, the greatest progress of introducing 'iron tools and tractors (machines)' made using wisdom, from a life of plowing fields by hand?",
    choices:["Expansion of spending","Improvement of productivity","Revival of barter","Completion of monopoly"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Even with the same time and the same human labor, increasing the amount of results you can produce many times or tens of times by using excellent tools, machines, and systems is called 'improvement of productivity.' A person who took a whole day by hand to dig one potato can, using a tractor, harvest 100 potatoes in one hour. When productivity rises, food and wealth overflow in large amounts in society, and even without everyone working long hours sweating like slaves, they can create free time (leisure) where everyone can live safely, leisurely, and richly. Wisdom makes labor easier." },
  { id:57, topic:"Trade and distribution", emoji:"🚢",
    question:"What is the wonderful meaning of the system of 'trade' or distribution, where you exchange rare salt or medicine you can never get in your own region for clothing held by people in a far, different region?",
    choices:["Going far away mixes up each other's country names and makes them vanish","By exchanging things made using each Earth land's 'strengths of resources and climate it is good at,' everyone can equally enjoy wealth that one region alone could never get","Doing trade shrinks the Earth's size to half","A rule that buying far-off goods always makes mold grow on the bills"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"On Earth there is always inequality of resources by region - cold places, warm places, places with many mountains, places near the sea. If you shut yourself in one village living self-sufficiently, people in regions where salt can't be gathered get sick and die. Humankind developed the wisdom of 'distribution and trade,' connecting and exchanging specialty products made using each land's strengths with far regions. This has created a global network of mutual aid, where all people worldwide share Earth's whole blessings with each other and can safely draw out wealth wherever they are." },
  { id:58, topic:"Information asymmetry", emoji:"🔍",
    question:"When you go to buy a tool, why should you not buy right away just by the price you saw at the first shop, but check around several other shops' and the market's prices (gather information)?",
    choices:["Walking a lot strengthens the friction of your shoe soles and makes you run faster","If there is an 'information gap (a state where only one side knows the truth)' between the seller and buyer, there is a danger of being made to buy at an unfairly high price (a rip-off) above the market rate and losing big","Going around many shops turns the bills' color into a beautiful gold","A law that buying at one shop makes the shop's person sad"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"In business there are surely bad people who, taking advantage of the buyer not knowing the true value or market rate (the average price) of goods, jack up the price 10 times the normal and try to swindle. In economics terms this is called 'information asymmetry.' To not fall into this trap, before opening your wallet, gathering 'information data' yourself by opening books or going around multiple shops is the strongest barrier. A person without knowledge has their money taken, and a person with correct information can protect themselves - this is the harsh reality of society." },
  { id:59, topic:"Donation and giving", emoji:"🎁",
    question:"Without seeking any return, the action of sharing your money or food with a person truly without money in trouble, or a person who is injured and can't work (donation or giving) - what is its true wisdom in society?",
    choices:["To just throw money into a ditch and deliberately make yourself poor for fun","By erasing 'people who can only turn to crime in despair' or 'people who starve to death' from society, and raising the whole town's safety (public order) and kindness, you can most surely protect, in turn, your own life and future safety","Giving money to others makes new money fall from the sky the next day","To put on airs over a person in trouble and feel like you became a great god"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The true nature of 'donation or giving' without seeking return is not mere self-sacrificing volunteering. It is investment into the wisest 'social safety net (defense line),' to prevent the terrifying collapse of public order where the bottom falls out of society and people in poverty can't live without committing crime. The gentle money you used today to save another's pain returns to you, in turn, as the greatest value of a safe town where you yourself aren't attacked by thieves tomorrow. Circulating kindness is humankind's greatest social wisdom for surviving without self-destructing." },
  { id:60, topic:"Becoming money's master", emoji:"🧭",
    question:"Having learned in Pack 2 of this app 'Wise World 3' about the system of trust behind much economics and bills, what is the true final goal in your own life?",
    choices:["To hoard the most money in the world and become a king who commands others and rules them with money","Not to become a slave of money, a tool of numbers, but to correctly see through the 'system of trust and thanks' behind the bills, use your wisdom to gently rule money, and master it to protect the human rights and happiness of yourself and those around you","To shop to the limit every day and fill your house with garbage, the end","To get a trophy for all-correct answers and quit studying entirely"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Congratulations! With this, all 30 questions of Pack 2 are finished. Money, if you use it one step wrong, turns into a terrifying devil's chain that makes people doubt, makes people betray, and steals people's freedom for life. But if you hold the 'compass of economic wisdom' you've learned in this quiz, you will no longer be deceived by the numbers on bills. Money is merely a convenient tool that makes the 'energy of trust' - born when you solve someone's trouble - easy to carry. Rather than being ruled by money, use your wisdom to become 'the master who gently controls' money. And, equal and fair with friends worldwide, cooperate to build with your own hands a gentle world where no one starves. Everyone around the world cheers for your wise independence!" },
  { id:61, topic:"Speed vs. safety", emoji:"🛣️",
    question:"You are heading home before it gets dark. There is a 'safe, wide detour' that takes 1 hour to walk, and a 'dangerous shortcut' that gets you home in 10 minutes but has crumbling footing and a risk of falling off a cliff. Which should you choose?",
    choices:["I want to get home and play sooner, so I run along the dangerous shortcut","Even if it takes longer and tires me out, I steadily walk home by the 'safe, wide detour' that has the lowest risk of losing my life","I close my eyes and decide which is better while running","I sit down on the shortcut and rest until it gets dark"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a basic problem about the 'trade-off' between time (speed) and safety, where gaining one means giving up the other. The 10-minute shortcut is tempting, but if the ground crumbles and you fall off a cliff, you could be badly injured or lose your life and never make it home again. An action that carries the risk that '99 times you are fine, but one failure ends your life' is the worst possible choice, both economically and in terms of survival odds, and must never be picked. Even at the cost of extra time and tired legs, choosing the safe road where your odds of surviving are close to 100% is the true wisdom of risk management." },
  { id:62, topic:"Preserving food", emoji:"🧂",
    question:"After a huge harvest, you have more fresh meat and fish than one person could ever eat. But it will all rot in a few days. What is the wise, lowest-risk action here?",
    choices:["It would be a waste to let it rot, so I eat it all by myself right now until my stomach is about to burst","I share it with friends and family to eat together, or I take the time and effort to cook it and turn it into 'preserved food' by salting or drying it","I leave it in the room until it rots, and eat it once it starts to smell","I bury it in the ground just as it is and hide it"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a trade-off between the 'immediate fullness right in front of you (consumption)' and putting in the effort of processing to save it for the future, the 'future safety (investment).' Forcing it all down alone risks severe food poisoning that wrecks your stomach and could cost you your life. By putting in the effort to salt and dry it (making dried food), you take away the water that the rot-causing germs need, turning it into a shield you can eat for months. And by sharing with friends and earning goodwill (trust), you build the best safety net: they will help you when you go hungry in the future." },
  { id:63, topic:"Peer pressure", emoji:"🗳️",
    question:"Five companions are doing a job together. When you discuss how to proceed next, 4 of them say, 'This way is easier, so let us ignore the rules and go ahead.' But from your view, that method has a big danger (a bug, a risk of an accident). How should you act?",
    choices:["The opinion of the 4-person majority (the crowd) must always be right, so I quietly go along","I am afraid of being disliked by my friends, so even though I know it is dangerous I say nothing and go along with everyone","Regardless of the number of people, I calmly explain the scientific and logical 'evidence of the danger,' and persuade everyone to switch to the safe method that follows the rules","I get angry and run off somewhere alone"],
    answerIndex:2,
    explanation:"The human tendency to be swept along by the crowd's opinion and make a wrong decision is called 'peer pressure (conformity pressure)' or the 'groupthink trap.' Majority vote is a handy system, but in the world of science and safety, 'how many people agree' is not one bit of proof of being right. Even if 4 people say 'it is fine,' ignoring the laws of physics or safety rules means an accident is 100% certain and everyone gets caught in it. If you truly value your companions' lives, the mark of a wise leader is the courage to overcome the fear of being disliked (the cost) and, based on solid evidence, raise your voice and say 'this is dangerous.'" },
  { id:64, topic:"Judgment in darkness", emoji:"🌑",
    question:"While traveling through a deep forest or unknown land, the sun sets completely and it becomes pitch dark (no light at all). You can also hear wild animals howling. What is the least bad way to act?",
    choices:["Trusting my gut, I rush on foot through the darkness, searching for the exit","Walking on recklessly carries a very high risk of falling off a cliff or getting lost, so I shelter behind a sturdy rock or up in a tree, stay alert to my surroundings, and 'wait quietly for morning to come'","I run around the darkness at full speed while shouting loudly","I lie spread-eagled on the ground, let my guard down completely, and sleep soundly"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a risk-management problem of weighing the 'risk of moving' against the 'risk of staying put.' Moving through pitch darkness is like walking across a minefield with your eyes shut: the odds of getting lost or falling soar. Staying put carries the risk of meeting wild animals or the cold, but if you hide behind a rock, mask your presence, and stay alert while gripping a tree branch as a weapon, you can keep your survival odds high. In a low-visibility situation where you cannot calculate the risk one step ahead, the worldwide iron rule is to 'stay still, endure, and wait for information (the light of day).'" },
  { id:65, topic:"Predicting flash floods", emoji:"🌊",
    question:"A fierce downpour finally stops abruptly and the sun comes out. The river in front of you still looks the same as always, but you really want to cross this river to the other bank right now. How do you judge it?",
    choices:["The rain has stopped and the weather is fine, so I judge that I can cross safely right now and jump in","Right after the rain stops, the huge amount of water that fell on the upper mountains is very likely to come surging down to you with a time lag (a flash flood), so I keep away from the river for a few hours and watch the situation","I go to the middle of the river and stop to check whether the water is rising","I figure I will be fine if I dash across in an instant"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The human brain has a dangerous thinking bug called 'normalcy bias,' where it conveniently feels safe based only on the situation right in front of it, thinking 'the rain has stopped, so it is safe now.' But if you look at the scientific cause and effect, the heavy rain soaks into the ground and turns into a fierce river flow, and there is always a 'time lag of several hours' before it reaches you downstream. Even with clear skies, the river's terror is only just beginning. Learn to grasp how nature works as data on a timeline, and to put the brakes on your brain's assumptions." },
  { id:66, topic:"The too-good-to-be-true trap", emoji:"📦",
    question:"A stranger adult says, 'If you carry this package to that town over there, I will give you, right now, enough money to live and play for a whole year.' You are not allowed to see what is inside. How do you decide?",
    choices:["It is a huge chance to become rich, so I gladly take on the package and carry it","Hiding the contents and offering an unnatural sum of money for a child's labor means I logically see through that 'there is 100% a crime behind this trap,' so I firmly refuse and flee at once","I negotiate one more time over how much I will be paid","I take only half of the package and try carrying it"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"As you learned in the Pack 2 economy, the size of the reward and the size of the risk are perfectly proportional. When you are offered an unnatural sum of money to carry a package whose contents are hidden, the contents are very likely 'illegal drugs' or 'stolen property.' If you carry it unknowingly and get caught, you pay the catastrophic cost of being locked away as a criminal in a dark prison for years, losing all the freedom in your life. When the two signals 'I do not know what is inside' and 'money with no reason' line up, that is a 100% alarm of a dangerous trap. Use your eyes of wisdom and protect your own life." },
  { id:67, topic:"Evacuation priorities", emoji:"🎒",
    question:"A huge earthquake or flood strikes, and you must evacuate your home right now. In your home are a precious toy, a heavy box of money, and many keepsakes full of memories. Which is the correct judgment for what to take when you evacuate?",
    choices:["I do not want to lose my treasures, so I stuff my bag full of heavy belongings, sling it on my back, and flee","Heavy luggage means I cannot run away and could lose my life, so I take only the 'lightest, minimum belongings absolutely needed to live,' such as water, minimal food, and medical supplies, and flee with both hands free","I take a full hour to carefully gather my belongings before moving","I take nothing but my single most favorite toy and flee"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a trade-off in an emergency between 'material property' and 'your own life (time and movement speed).' Fleeing with a heavy bag on your back makes your walking speed drop dramatically, so you cannot escape a collapsing building or run from rushing water. Also, if both hands are full when you trip, you can hit your head hard and be unable to move. No matter how expensive an item or precious a keepsake, if you do not survive, all of its value becomes zero. In an emergency, make the cold, correct decision in one second: 'throw away everything except your life.'" },
  { id:68, topic:"Not spreading infection", emoji:"🤧",
    question:"You wake up in the morning feeling a little unwell, with a cough. Today is the day of an important job (or a school test) where you gather with all your precious companions to build a large structure. How should you act?",
    choices:["I do not want to be a burden to everyone, so I hide that I feel unwell, go to work as usual, and push myself until evening","I think of the 'risk of passing my illness to my companions and wiping out the whole team,' honestly tell the people at home or the leader, and rest quietly at home to recover","I hold my breath the whole time so that I do not cough, and keep working","Partway through the job, I go home silently without telling anyone"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is an advanced risk-management problem of weighing your own 'sense of responsibility (the feeling that you must go)' against the whole team's 'risk of spreading infection.' Pushing yourself to go to work looks admirable at first glance, but from a medical view, the virus you breathe out can infect your coworkers one after another, and a few days later the whole team falls ill and the project comes to a complete stop, the worst kind of secondary disaster. When you feel unwell, 'resting is the most responsible action of all toward society.'" },
  { id:69, topic:"Stopping rumors", emoji:"📢",
    question:"In the village you hear a rumor: 'From the next town, a terrifying monster carrying a bad disease is running this way right now!' Everyone is panicking and making a huge fuss. What action should you take first?",
    choices:["It is a serious event, so I rush to tell all my other friends and family, 'A monster is coming, run!'","Even when I hear the terrifying rumor, I calm my heart once, coolly check whether there is a 'source (who said it first)' or 'solid scientific evidence,' and make sure I am not swept up by the false rumor","I believe the rumor and rampage, smashing all the furniture in the house","To defeat the monster, I grab a weapon alone and run out of town"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"The phenomenon where groundless lies or mistaken fear spread explosively from person to person during a disaster or emergency is called 'false rumors (disinformation)' or 'mass panic.' A person whose brain is ruled by the emotion of fear becomes a 'rumor courier,' spreading it to others without checking. When this happens, the escape roads that are truly needed jam up, fights break out, and society destroys itself. When you hear a rumor, first make the baton of information 'stop dead' with you. Then check trustworthy books or adults' data, and hold up the shield of confirming the facts." },
  { id:70, topic:"The risk of lending", emoji:"🪓",
    question:"A friend asks to borrow, for a few days, the very sharp 'axe (a tool)' that he treasures. But that friend always handles tools roughly and has broken things many times before. How do you reply?",
    choices:["Refusing would worsen my relationship with my friend, so I lend it with a smile anyway, resigned to it being broken","If the tool breaks I cannot do my own work and my life is at stake, so based on the past data I gently explain my reasons and either set a safe condition like 'you may use it only while you are with me,' or propose a way that will not damage it","I shout him down at the top of my voice, 'You always break things, so no!' and chase him away","I pretend to lend it, but hand over a broken axe that does not cut at all"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a dilemma between your 'relationship with your friend (the wish to lend it)' and the 'protection of your own precious property (the risk of it being broken).' Lending it anyway while ignoring the risk data, just because you do not want to hurt the other person, is simply giving up on thinking. When the tool actually breaks, your friend feels awkward, your tool is lost, and you reach the worst outcome. Risk management is not merely refusing the other person, but using your head to come up with an 'alternative plan (a different approach)' that lowers your own risk while still meeting their needs, and negotiating as equals." },
  { id:71, topic:"Boiling water", emoji:"🚰",
    question:"There is water you drew from a nearby well. It looks completely clear and sparkling clean. But this water is from after yesterday's heavy rain. When you drink the water, what should you do?",
    choices:["It looks clear and I am terribly thirsty, so I gulp it down right now just as it is","Even at the cost of the 'time and fuel to bring it to a rolling boil,' I make sure to wipe out 100% of the invisible germs before drinking it safely","I put one pretty stone into the water before drinking","I say a prayer to the water before drinking"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a trade-off between 'the speed of quenching your thirst right now' and 'the medical risk of wrecking your stomach and getting seriously ill later.' As you have learned again and again, water after a disaster, no matter how beautiful it looks, has harmful substances and germs from the ground mixed in. Someone who skimps on the up-front cost, thinking 'making a fire is a hassle' or 'firewood (fuel) is a waste,' and drinks it raw, pays a worst-case cost tens of thousands of times heavier: dying a few days later from violent diarrhea. Do not begrudge paying the right cost for safety." },
  { id:72, topic:"Lured into danger", emoji:"🕳️",
    question:"A group of friends teases you: 'Let us go exploring inside that deep, about-to-collapse cave! Anyone who does not come is a coward!' Everyone is about to go inside. How do you act?",
    choices:["It stings to be called a coward, and since everyone is going, I go into the cave with them too","Insults and teasing have not one bit of scientific basis, so I completely ignore them, never enter the dangerous place myself, and with all my might stop the others too, saying 'it really is dangerous, let us not'","I do not go in myself, but stand and wait right at the very edge of the cave entrance","I get angry at my friends and throw stones at them"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"A person who deliberately eggs others into dangerous behavior by stirring up the fear of being left out or by pricking their pride with insults (like 'coward') is a 'tempter of risk.' The most common cause of accidents among 9-to-12-year-olds is losing to this peer pressure and getting badly hurt while trying to 'look cool.' A wise person completely separates, in their mind, the verbal insults (emotion) from the physical danger of the about-to-collapse cave (fact) when judging. True courage is not jumping into a reckless challenge, but having a strong, independent heart that can say 'NO' to danger." },
  { id:73, topic:"Cutting corners and safety", emoji:"🏗️",
    question:"You are building your house's roof, or a wooden bridge for everyone to cross. You want to finish fast and play, so is it okay to cut corners (use fewer nails, use thinner wood) to speed up?",
    choices:["Finishing right now feels good, so I cut corners where they cannot be seen and finish fast","Cutting corners leads to a 'huge accident where it collapses in an instant and badly injures someone' the moment a strong wind blows or a heavy person steps on it later, so even if it takes time I build it sturdily by the rules","I make it look finished, then stop the work partway and go off to play","I just keep a close watch to see whether other people are cutting corners"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a trade-off between 'your own laziness wanting to take it easy now' and 'the collapse of future safety.' The structure of a building and the forces of physics are very honest: the moment gravity or wind energy concentrates on the weak spot (the bug) of a corner that a human looked away from, destruction strikes all at once with a snap. The one who gets hurt then might be you yourself, or your precious family. In work, the craftsman's wisdom of 'honestly building the unseen foundation sturdily, even when no one is watching' protects society's trust and everyone's lives for a long time." },
  { id:74, topic:"Spending vs. investing", emoji:"🧰",
    question:"You worked hard and saved up an allowance (a budget) you can spend freely. At the shop are a 'flashy toy' you can brag about to friends right now, and a 'sturdy work tool' that will make your future work speed 3 times faster. Which is the smart thing to buy?",
    choices:["I want my friends to call me amazing right now, so I buy the flashy toy","Rather than bragging right now, I buy the 'sturdy work tool (an investment)' that raises my future productivity and safely earns me even more money","I do not spend any of the money; I bury it deep in the ground and forget it","I buy neither, and instead buy snacks to the limit and eat them all in one day"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the advanced choice between 'consumption' and 'investment' that also appeared in the Pack 2 economy. Buying the toy brings the fun of that moment (consumption), but the allowance vanishes and your abilities do not change at all. Buying the work tool, on the other hand, becomes a seed (investment) that lifts your future 'productivity (the amount of wealth you can make in one hour)' many times over. A wise person does not merely spend the money in hand, but uses it to upgrade their own skills and tools, steadily strengthening the legs of their independence. Make money your tool to command." },
  { id:75, topic:"Preventing secondary disasters", emoji:"🚨",
    question:"The old building in front of you is crumbling apart from an earthquake or fire. In the dangerous area right next to that building, your friend is hurt, has fallen, and is crying. What is the very first 'emergency judgment' you should make?",
    choices:["I want to save my friend in a hurry, so without looking at the surroundings I dash straight in to where they have fallen","Considering the danger that if I rush in, the building could collapse from above and bury both of us (a secondary disaster), I first check the 'safety of the surroundings (above and behind)' for 3 seconds, secure safety or call for an adult's help, and only then approach","I get scared, abandon my friend, and run away","I keep shouting at my fallen friend, 'Hurry, run over here!'"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"In emergency medicine and survival, the absolute Rule 1 drilled in most strictly worldwide is 'checking the safety of the surroundings.' When someone has fallen in front of you, you want to rush over in a panic, but if that spot is 'under a wall about to collapse' or 'in a pit where poison gas has pooled,' the moment you approach, you too get caught and fall, the rescuers drop to zero, and everyone dies. This is called a 'secondary disaster.' When you help someone, first keep yourself absolutely safe; this is a cold but correct iron rule." },
  { id:76, topic:"The danger of wild animals", emoji:"🐻",
    question:"In the forest you find a tiny, very cute 'baby of a wild bear or other predator' toddling along by itself. You cannot see the mother bear anywhere around. How do you act?",
    choices:["It is cute, so I get close to cuddle it or give it food from my pocket to make friends","I never go near it; I mask my presence and quickly, quietly leave the spot. Right near the baby, a 'terrifying mother animal,' grown extremely ferocious to protect her young, is surely lurking in the shadows","I take the baby animal home and make it a pet","I chase the baby animal around while shouting loudly"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is risk management built on knowing the habits (the evidence) of wild creatures. When a predator's baby is alone, it does not mean the mother slacked off and vanished somewhere. She is searching for food in the shadows nearby, or watching you closely. The moment a human comes near her young, a wild animal judges it as 'an enemy attacking to kill my child,' flips its wild switch to maximum, and charges to kill you, risking its own life. Do not be fooled by the 'cuteness (emotion)' of appearances; predict the 'reality of the defensive instinct (fact)' of the natural world, and keep a safe distance." },
  { id:77, topic:"Fair sharing of resources", emoji:"🤲",
    question:"A huge disaster or drought strikes, and the village's precious 'drinking water' and 'medicine' fall drastically short, nowhere near enough for everyone. In this crisis, what is the least bad judgment?",
    choices:["To survive myself, I use my strength to forcibly seize other people's share of the water and medicine","Fighting over them means people get injured and society destroys itself, so everyone discusses it and decides a fair rule to hand them out in order, starting with the weakest, such as 'small children, pregnant women, and the sick,' and we share","I pour all the water and medicine onto the ground so that no one can use it","I give up, and everyone sits down on the spot and cries"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is society's risk management in an extreme state (a crisis) where resources run critically short. If you scrap the rules here and allow a world of violence (the law of the jungle) where the strong seize from the weak, a war of killing breaks out in the village, and in the end everyone perishes from injury or illness. Humans have wisdom precisely so that, in such a crisis, they can invent 'rules (a social contract)' to maximize the whole group's odds of survival. The kind and rational system of handing things out in order, starting with the weakest lives we must protect most, is what has let humankind survive through a harsh history." },
  { id:78, topic:"Respecting privacy", emoji:"🔒",
    question:"On the internet or in conversation, someone is amusing themselves by trying to spread, without permission, your precious friend's 'secret data or memory of a past failure they are embarrassed about.' How do you act?",
    choices:["It sounds fun, so I join in and blab the secret to everyone else too","Spreading another person's secrets or unwanted information without permission deeply wounds their heart and human rights; it is 'violence (bullying)' that completely destroys trust and must never be done, so with anger I make them stop","I pretend I did not see it, and copy my friend's secret into my notebook","I tease my friend, saying 'It is lame that your secret got out'"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is about the danger of treating another person's 'privacy (secrets)' as a half-joke. The power of words and the internet to spread is especially terrifying: once another person's embarrassing rumor has spread, it can never be fully collected back and erased. The person it happened to may fall into despair and become mentally ill, or lose the energy to live. Become a person who can imagine another's pain as your own and put the brakes on a group that is amusing itself, saying 'that is wrong, stop it.' Protecting others' dignity comes back around to build a safe world where everyone protects you when you are in a crisis." },
  { id:79, topic:"The lost-child rule", emoji:"🧍",
    question:"In an unfamiliar big city, an endless wide desert, or a forest, you get separated from your family or companions and become 'lost.' There is no one around who seems likely to help you. How should you act?",
    choices:["To find my family, I cry out and keep wandering frantically in all sorts of directions no matter what","Wandering only takes me farther away and harder to find, so I calm my heart, plant my feet firmly on the 'safe place where I was definitely last with my family,' and wait without moving for them to find me","I climb a tall tree on the spot and spend the night alone","I silently follow right behind a stranger adult and walk"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is survival evidence for when you are lost (the risk of moving versus the risk of waiting). When separated, if a child panics and wanders in all directions, they cross paths with the family's search route, drift farther and farther, and become completely lost. Family and search teams always look centered on 'the place where you were last separated.' That is exactly why, when lost, you must keep the worldwide rescue iron rule of 'do not move one step from the spot (Hug a Tree: hug a tree and wait).' The patient wisdom of not moving raises the odds of reuniting with your family the fastest." },
  { id:80, topic:"Putting out a fire", emoji:"🧯",
    question:"After a campfire you used for cooking or warmth, the fire has gone completely out, leaving only black charcoal and ash. Before you return to your home or tent, what is the last thing to do?",
    choices:["There are no red flames to be seen, so I judge it fully extinguished, leave it as is, and walk away","To prevent the danger that an unseen 'tremendously hot ember' hidden deep in the charcoal could become a big fire when the wind blows later, I pour buckets of water over it again and again and make sure it has cooled completely","I pile lots of dry leaves on top of the charcoal to hide it","I blow hard on the ash with a fire-blowing rod and scatter it on the wind"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the cold physics evidence of handling fire. After a campfire, when the surface is covered in black charcoal and white ash, the human eye conveniently feels safe (normalcy bias), thinking 'it is already out.' But inside the charcoal, fierce 'embers' of several hundred degrees survive for hours, hoarding heat like a thermos by keeping out the air. If you walk away like that, the moment a strong wind at night feeds in oxygen, the charcoal flares up explosively again, causing a big fire (a wildfire) that burns the surrounding forest and tents to nothing in an instant. The wisdom of pouring water until the sizzling sound stops completely protects nature and lives worldwide." },
  { id:81, topic:"Time and money", emoji:"⏰",
    question:"Shopping quiz. At a far market '1 hour's walk' from your home, potatoes sell for 50 coins. At the shop 'right next door' to your home, the same potatoes sell for 100 coins. Where is it smartest to buy?",
    choices:["50 is definitely the smaller number, so no matter what, you should always spend 1 hour walking to the far market","You weigh 'the 2-hour round trip, which is your own precious life-time' and 'the energy you burn walking,' calculate whether it is worth spending those 2 hours on something else like studying or work, and choose the better option yourself","You go to the most expensive shop and pay the clerk extra money","You do not know which is better, so you give up on buying potatoes"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is an advanced balancing problem between the numbers of money and 'your own time (opportunity cost).' Saving 50 coins is tempting, but to do it you pay the cost of sacrificing the '2-hour' round trip. If you could earn 500 coins working in those 2 hours, then spending 2 hours to pinch 50 coins means, by subtraction, you are taking a 'big loss of 450 coins.' On the other hand, if today you have nothing to do and endless time to spare, then going far for some exercise and saving 50 coins becomes the right answer. There is not just one correct answer. Develop an adult brain that converts time into money and calculates." },
  { id:82, topic:"Caution toward the unknown", emoji:"🍒",
    question:"In the forest you find 'a beautiful fruit of a brand-new species, totally unknown, that is absolutely not in any book or adult's teaching you have seen.' You are terribly hungry. How should you act?",
    choices:["It looks delicious and has a beautiful color, so I eat all of it right now to fill my stomach","Considering the risk that unknown food may hide a deadly poison that destroys a human's organs in an instant, I 'never put in my mouth' anything not scientifically proven 100% safe","I let a friend eat just a little and experiment to see if their stomach goes bad","I rinse the fruit once with water and then gulp it down whole"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the wisdom of caution toward the 'unknown (risk)' in survival. When a plant or fruit in nature has a beautiful color or sweet smell, it is not so that humans will find it tasty. Rather, it is very likely a 'fierce poison defense weapon' that evolved on its own so that animals would not eat it. The rule of a wise survivor is not 'eat only what you know is safe,' but the strict subtractive thinking 'treat anything not proven 100% safe as poison.' Do not lose to immediate hunger and gamble your life." },
  { id:83, topic:"Slow and steady", emoji:"🪵",
    question:"There are 10 bundles of heavy firewood. When you forced yourself to carry all 10 at once, you wobbled, dropped the load many times, and it took 30 minutes. When you split it into 5 trips of 2 bundles each, you finished carrying it safely in 10 minutes. What wisdom do you learn from this result?",
    choices:["That carrying lots of luggage at once trains your muscles and looks cool","Make haste slowly (the more you hurry, the more you take the safe, sure method). Correctly calculating your body's limit and splitting the load is, in the end, the fastest and most 'productive' way","That not carrying the luggage and leaving it on the spot takes the least time","That from next time, you should make someone else carry it all"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a trade-off between 'the impatience of wanting to finish in one go' and 'errors (failures) caused by the body's physical limits.' The more impatient a human is, the more they want to overrate their strength and aim for a reckless single strike (a shortcut), but they usually lose their balance, fail badly, have to start over from the beginning, and lose many times the time and energy. Calmly facing the data of your own limits and splitting the task into small, sure pieces to stack up, a low-risk method, makes the total speed (productivity) overwhelmingly faster." },
  { id:84, topic:"Clothing as defense", emoji:"🦟",
    question:"On a hot summer day, you go to work in a thorny thicket or a deep forest where terrifying poisonous bugs (mosquitoes and ticks) lurk in great numbers. What clothing is the most correct choice for risk management?",
    choices:["It is very hot, so I go in cool, easy-to-move short sleeves, shorts, and bare feet","Even at the cost of sweating in the heat, so that sharp thorns and insect stingers do not reach my skin directly, I wear thick-fabric 'long sleeves, long pants, and sturdy shoes,' completely hiding my skin","It would be a waste to dirty my clothes, so I go naked wearing nothing","I wear the most gorgeous, prettiest clothes I have at home"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is a dilemma between 'the comfort of wanting to be cool right now (emotion)' and 'the defense of your skin (safety).' If you bare your skin because it is hot and go into a deep thicket, not only do thorns leave your skin bloody, but mosquitoes and ticks carrying terrifying disease viruses (such as malaria and dengue fever) bite you in great numbers, and you fall a few days later with a 40-degree fever, taking on a risk tens of thousands of times more terrifying. Clothing is 'the first and strongest medical barrier,' using the physical wall of fabric. For safety, have the wisdom to endure the present discomfort (the heat)." },
  { id:85, topic:"Controlling anger", emoji:"😤",
    question:"Partway through a job or discussion with a friend, the other person says something unreasonable and mean to you, or carelessly breaks your precious tool. Your chest burns red-hot with anger, and you feel like punching them. How should you act?",
    choices:["Driven by the emotion of anger, I yell at the top of my voice and punch them back with all my might","If anger hijacks my brain I cannot calculate calmly, and I take a big loss like starting a violent incident and getting arrested by the police, so I close my eyes once, 'take 3 deep breaths' to cool my brain, and convey the facts in words","I am frustrated, so I go home and smash the wall of my own room with all my might","Without saying anything, I secretly stuff lots of stones into the other person's shoes"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is control over your own 'emotion of anger (impulse)' and 'the prediction of the worst result that follows' (anger management). The moment a human feels anger, the primitive part of the brain (the amygdala) goes to full power, and the switch of the frontal lobe, which governs reason, temporarily turns completely off. If you wield violence on the emotion of those 'few seconds when your head has gone foolish,' you pay the worst cost: badly injuring the other person, becoming a criminal, or the trust you have built vanishing in an instant. The few seconds of patience to breathe deeply, send oxygen to your brain, and switch reason back on save your life from ruin." },
  { id:86, topic:"Life over tools", emoji:"⛰️",
    question:"You accidentally drop the very expensive, precious 'iron kitchen knife (a tool)' you use for crafts and work into the bushes at the bottom of a deep, crumbling cliff. How do you judge it?",
    choices:["I do not want to lose my precious, expensive tool, so without even a rope I hurry, slide down the cliff slope, and go to pick it up","A tool can be rebought someday if I pay money, but my own life can never be rebought. If the footing is dangerous, I give up on forcing my way to get it, or I call for an adult with safe tools to help","From the top of the cliff, I keep shouting at the knife, 'Come back'","I hurl lots of heavy stones toward the place where the knife fell"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the ultimate trade-off between a tool's 'money value' and your own 'physical safety.' When you lose something expensive, the human brain fills with impatience and the wish not to take a loss (loss-aversion bias), and the surrounding danger becomes invisible. But by the laws of physics, you can calculate 100% that a human with no rope going down a crumbling cliff will fall headlong, break their skull, and lose their life. A tool is an 'interchangeable part' that money or labor can always replace, but your life is the one 'irreplaceable top secret' there is only one of in the world. Never mistake the weight of an object for the weight of a life." },
  { id:87, topic:"Evidence over authority", emoji:"📚",
    question:"About how to cure a certain illness, two adults in the village give completely different advice. Person A says, 'Because it is a saying from long ago, you will be cured if you chant this spell,' and Person B says, 'A science book says that if you boil this medicinal herb and drink it, the ingredient works.' Which do you believe?",
    choices:["Person A is older and has a longer beard, so I believe what Person A says","Without being fooled by old sayings or the speaker's appearance (authority), I believe and carry out 'Person B's book advice,' which carries actual treatment data and experimental evidence (scientific evidence)","I mix the two opinions and eat the raw herb while chanting the spell","I cannot believe either, so I rampage and shout loudly in the room"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the risk management of whether to judge the 'correctness' of information by the speaker's age or appearance (authority), or by 'solid factual data (evidence).' Among old sayings there is wonderful wisdom, but mixed in are also wrong magic spells and dangerous assumptions that actually worsen illness. In a decision of medicine or science where a human life is at stake, only those with logical eyes who coolly press for 'whether there are statistics or evidence (data) in the world that it actually cured someone' - not who said it - can avoid the trap and survive." },
  { id:88, topic:"Treating small wounds", emoji:"🦶",
    question:"Partway through outdoor work, a small thorn sticks into the sole of your foot and a little blood comes out. But right now you are in the middle of playing happily with everyone (or busily working). What do you do about this small injury?",
    choices:["It is embarrassing to tell everyone about such a small wound, so I keep it secret and keep moving, leaving it until night","Considering the risk that invisible dirt germs enter through the small wound and later my whole foot rots so I cannot walk, I stop once, immediately wash it with clean water, and treat it with disinfection","I deliberately rub the wound's blood off with mud","I push the thorn in the sole of my foot even deeper with my finger"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"This is the problem of leaving a bug, where you leave a small risk thinking 'oh well' and let it grow into an irreparable catastrophe later. If you look at the history of medicine, no matter how healthy and strong a human is, there have been millions of accidents where germs (tetanus or sepsis) entering through a small wound spread through the whole body's blood a few days later, and in an environment with no doctor, the foot was amputated or the life was lost. The secret of risk management lies in the daily habit of diligent self-management: 'at the earliest stage (right now), when the risk is smallest and easiest to crush, treat it surely and nip it in the bud.'" },
  { id:89, topic:"Signs of disaster", emoji:"🌋",
    question:"You live near a volcano or a large river. One day, an eerie rumbling you have never heard echoes out, and the wild animals around you all flee from the mountain at once. But the other adult humans laugh easily, saying 'It is the same as always, so it is fine.' How should you act?",
    choices:["The adults around me are laughing, so I relax too and sleep in the house as usual","I trust the clear sign of a great disaster (warning data) that the natural world is sending, am not swept along by the carelessness of the people around me, and even if it is just me and my family, I gather my things at once and evacuate early to safe high ground","I wait still on the spot until the adults flee","I chase after the animals and go deep into the mountain"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Just before a big disaster, many humans convince themselves 'only I am fine' or 'the others are not moving, so it is still okay,' are too slow to flee, and all perish together. This worst bug of the group brain is called 'pluralistic ignorance' or 'normalcy bias.' The creatures of great nature, with senses keener than humans', catch the earth's dangerous tiny tremors and the smell of gas (data) and take defensive action in one second. Do not watch the 'human mood (emotion)' around you; trust only the data of nature's 'physical signs (fact),' and become a wise survivor who can dash to evacuate as the first penguin, earlier than anyone." },
  { id:90, topic:"Risk management summary", emoji:"🦉",
    question:"A question for you, who have cleared Pack 3 of this app 'Wise World 3.' What kind of power is the true essence of 'the best risk management (predicting risk)' for living through the world safely, wisely, and independently?",
    choices:["The power to cry out loudly after something has happened and have someone help me","The power to not be fooled by the emotion or assumption in front of me, to use scientific data to read ahead, in many patterns in my head, the future cause-and-effect route of 'if I do this, what is the worst result that happens next,' and to decide a safe route myself and move before it becomes dangerous","The power to grow my muscles thicker than others and punch down every danger","The power to keep believing easily that nothing bad could ever happen to me"],
    answerIndex:1,
    explanation:"Congratulations! With this, all 30 questions of Pack 3 are complete. The real world is not a place that is always safe and kind, like a fairy tale. Sudden disasters, traps of sweet words, the peer pressure of groups - dangers that try to drag you into ruin are always lurking. But if you hold the 'compass of trade-offs and risk management' you learned in this pack, there is nothing more to fear. Risk management is not becoming timid and shutting yourself in a room; it is properly studying the true form of danger (the laws of physics and the bugs of human psychology), storing it as data in your head, smartly avoiding dangerous places, and going on a grand adventure through the world freely and powerfully - 'the greatest, strongest shield of wisdom.' Using the wise survival intelligence lit in your brain, keep surely protecting your own life and the future of your precious companions. Everyone in the world cheers from the heart for the success of your journey of independence!" }
];
